Flutter
Flutter is an open-source UI (User Interface) software development kit (SDK) created by Google.
It is used to build natively compiled applications for mobile (Android & iOS), web, desktop, 
and embedded devices from a single codebase.
The Core Problem it Solves: 
Traditionally, if you wanted an app on both Android and iOS, you had to write it twice:
once in Kotlin/Java (Android) and once in Swift/Objective-C (iOS). 
Flutter allows you to write the code once and deploy it everywhere.

"Everything is a Widget"

In Flutter, the user interface is built entirely out of Widgets.
A widget is a declaration of what the UI should look like.
Structural elements (like a button or menu) are widgets.
Stylistic elements (like a font or color scheme) are widgets.
Layout aspects (like padding or centering) are also widgets.

Widgets nest inside each other to create a hierarchical structure called the Widget Tree.

The Two Core Types of Widgets:
StatelessWidget:
Concept: Immutable. Their appearance cannot change while the app is running based on user behavior or data updates.
Examples: A static Text label, an Icon, or a company logo.

StatefulWidget:
Concept: Dynamic. They maintain a "State" object that can change over time. When the state changes, the widget rebuilds itself to show the new data.
Examples: A slider, a checkbox, a counter button, or a text input field.

Key Feature: Hot Reload vs. Hot Restart
Flutter drastically speeds up development time with these two features:
Hot Reload: Inject updated source code files into the running Dart Virtual Machine. It updates the UI in under a 
    second without losing the app's current state (e.g., if you are 3 screens deep into testing a form, you won't get kicked back to the login page).
Hot Restart: Fully restarts the app, destroying the current state and rebuilding the widget tree from scratch.


import 'package:flutter/material.dart'; // Imports pre-made Google Material widgets

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp()); // The entry point of the application
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      home: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: const Text('Student Intro App'),
        ),
        body: const Center(
          child: Text('Welcome to Flutter!'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}


MaterialApp: The root widget that establishes the design scheme (Material Design) and configures navigation routes.
Scaffold: Provides a baseline structural layout for a mobile screen. It gives you ready-made properties for an appBar, 
          a body, a floatingActionButton, and a navigation drawer.
Center: A layout widget that centers its child widget exactly in the middle of the available space.

Advantages and Disadvantages 
Advantages:
Single Codebase: Saves time, effort, and cost by avoiding duplicate codebases.
Native Performance: Compiles directly to native machine code.
Rich Catalog of Widgets: Huge ecosystem of pre-designed widgets following Material Design (Google) and Cupertino (Apple) standards.
Strong Community Support: Highly popular on GitHub and StackOverflow, backed heavily by Google.
Disadvantages:
Larger File Sizes: Because the Flutter engine is bundled directly into the app package, the initial installation file (.apk or .ipa) is usually larger than a purely native app.
New Language Barrier: Requires learning Dart instead of sticking to standard web tools (HTML/CSS) or native tools.


Prerequisites
Before starting, make sure you have:
Flutter SDK installed on your computer.
VS Code installed.
The Flutter and Dart extensions installed inside VS Code (go to the Extensions tab on the left, search for "Flutter", and click Install).

Step 1: Create a New Flutter Project
Open VS Code.
Open the Command Palette by pressing Ctrl + Shift + P (Windows/Linux) or Cmd + Shift + P (Mac).
Type flutter and select Flutter: New Project.
Select Application from the list.
Choose a folder on your computer where you want to save your project.
Type a name for your app (e.g., my_first_app) and hit Enter.
Note: Use lowercase letters and underscores only. No spaces or special characters!
VS Code will now generate all the necessary files. This might take a minute the first time.

Step 2: Understand the Project Folder Structure
Once the project loads, look at the Explorer sidebar on the left. While there are many folders, you only need to focus on two things starting out:
lib/ folder: This is the most important folder. All your Flutter code lives here.
lib/main.dart: The main entry point of your application. This is the file you will be editing.
pubspec.yaml: The configuration file where you manage assets (images, fonts) and add external packages/libraries.

📝 Step 3: Write Your Code
Open lib/main.dart. You will see a lot of default template code with comments. Let’s clear that out and write a clean, simple "Hello World" app from scratch.
Delete everything in main.dart and paste this code:

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      debugShowCheckedModeBanner: false, // Removes the red debug banner
      home: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: const Text('My First App'),
          backgroundColor: Colors.blueGrey,
        ),
        body: const Center(
          child: Text(
            'Hello, Flutter!',
            style: TextStyle(fontSize: 28, color: Colors.blueGrey),
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 4: Choose Your Device (Target)
Before running the app, you need to tell VS Code where to display it.
Look at the bottom-right corner of the VS Code status bar. You will see the current target device (it might say something like Windows (windows-x64), Chrome, or No Device).
Click on that device name.
A dropdown menu will appear at the top of the screen.
Select your preferred target:
Web (Chrome / Edge): The fastest and easiest way to test without setting up emulators.
Android Emulator / iOS Simulator: If you have Android Studio or Xcode installed.
Windows / macOS (Desktop): Runs the app as a native desktop window.

Step 5: Run the App
Look at the top-right corner of VS Code and look for the Play icon (or press F5 on your keyboard).
Click Run without Debugging (or Start Debugging).
The Debug Console at the bottom of VS Code will open up, showing the build progress.
After a few seconds, your app will launch on your selected device!

Step 6: Test "Hot Reload"
Now for the magic of Flutter! Keep your app running on the screen alongside VS Code:
In main.dart, change the text 'Hello, Flutter!' to something else, like 'Coding is fun!'.
Press Ctrl + S (or Cmd + S on Mac) to save the file.

